I was very used to wearing a thick coat as the temperature was a constant 10 degrees below zero and it was dark for most of the day, and one day in winter I took my coat off and realized I couldn’t feel my arms and was wondering why I had stopped breathing. But when we moved to South Florida, most days are sunny with a gentle breeze so not only do I wear a thick coat, but a light jacket and a scarf too, just to feel breathing again.

The year in Turkey was good to me. I met quite a few people from Turkey coming up to our tents there and approached them here in Turkey. And the local people have great respect for Jewish people, a few are very religious, there are synagogues in Tehran and I love the Cairo Museum.

It was also great to see Turkey on the map in the Oscar news!

Jordan was absorbed into Saudi Arabia but it still had a lot of Palestinians there after the first Israeli-Arab war. It was also pretty good for excommunicated Israelis – not immaterial for another reason.

But living in America is the best. People are grateful, friendly and beyond expectations, nobody is excommunicated; while Jews live in New York they live like as we do wherever we go. Nice apartments, luxury cars – and we think of ourselves as poor people.

I love America. It is on my wish list that eventually I too will die in America.
